<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="278" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1127,1766]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1127,1153]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1966" box="[280,366,1128,1154]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Cestrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[280,366,1128,1154]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Cestrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1837" box="[771,881,1127,1153]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cryptinae">Cryptinae</taxonomicName>
genera by the following combination of features: (1) tip of ventral valve of ovipositor with a dorsal lobe that encloses dorsal valve; (2) ovipositor tip with a distinctly scabrous (microsculptured) area just basad of the teeth (
<figureCitation box="[797,887,1199,1225]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,597,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-228@4.[151,1436,597,1891]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cestrus itatiensis sp. nov., Holotype female. A. Head, frontal view. B. Propodeum, dorsal view. C. Apex of ovipositor, left side. D. Dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4401562" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4401562/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
), (3) T1 rather slender, with anterolateral tooth, spiracle placed approximately at midlength; (4) mandible ventral tooth a little longer than dorsal tooth; (5) pleural carina of propodeum complete, even if weak; (6) areolet pentagonal, about as wide as high; (7) crossvein 3r-m and 2r-m distinctly convergent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="278" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1127,1766]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1343,1369]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1966" box="[322,408,1344,1370]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Cestrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[322,408,1344,1370]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Cestrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a member of the 
<taxonomicName box="[632,730,1343,1369]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Gabunia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[632,730,1343,1369]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Gabunia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group of genera (
<bibRefCitation author="Santos, B. F." box="[930,1074,1343,1369]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" pagination="650 - 676" refId="ref4794" refString="Santos, B. F. (2017) Phylogeny and reclassification of Cryptini (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae, Cryptinae), with implications for ichneumonid higher-level classification. Systematic Entomology, 42 (4), 650 - 676. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12238" type="journal article" year="2017">Santos 2017</bibRefCitation>
), one of the few major clades of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Santos" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[151,244,1379,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Cryptini">Cryptini</taxonomicName>
that is clearly morphologically diagnosable; genera of the group have the ventral tooth of mandible longer than dorsal one; fore tibia strongly inflated; spiracle of T1 placed approximately at midlength; and ventral valve of ovipositor apically partially enclosing dorsal valve. These traits have convergently evolved in other groups of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Santos" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[151,244,1487,1513]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Cryptini">Cryptini</taxonomicName>
and at least some of them seem to be adaptations to attack deeply concealed hosts (
<bibRefCitation author="Santos, B. F. &amp; Perrard, A." box="[1165,1425,1487,1513]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" pagination="1430 - 1439" refId="ref4736" refString="Santos, B. F. &amp; Perrard, A. (2018) Testing the Dutilleul syndrome: host use drives the convergent evolution of multiple traits in parasitic wasps. Journal of Evolutionary Biology, 31 (10), 1430 - 1439. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jeb. 13343" type="journal article" year="2018">Santos &amp; Perrard 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Among the genera showing this morphological syndrome, the distinctly microsculptured area in the ventral valve of the ovipositor is a distinctive feature of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1966" box="[598,684,1560,1586]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Cestrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[598,684,1560,1586]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Cestrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, found only in the closely related genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Aguiar." authorityName="Aguiar." box="[1141,1378,1559,1585]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Dineotropica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1141,1289,1560,1585]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Dineotropica</emphasis>
Aguiar.
</taxonomicName>
Species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1966" box="[232,318,1596,1622]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Cestrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[232,318,1596,1622]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Cestrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated from 
<taxonomicName box="[623,771,1596,1621]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Dineotropica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[623,771,1596,1621]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Dineotropica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the epomia long (
<emphasis box="[1093,1123,1596,1621]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">vs.</emphasis>
short); T1 distinctly bent in lateral view (
<emphasis box="[299,329,1632,1657]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">vs.</emphasis>
almost straight); and crossveins 2r-m and 3r-m distinctly convergent (
<emphasis box="[1118,1148,1632,1657]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">vs.</emphasis>
subparallel).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,527,1667,1694]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1127,1766]" box="[199,527,1667,1694]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,289,1667,1693]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Biology</emphasis>
. Hosts are unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="278" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1127,1766]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1703,1729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="278">Distribution</emphasis>
. The genus is confined to the Neotropical Region, and at least the currently described species seem to be absent from lowland forests; all known records are from altitudes ranging from 
<quantity box="[1106,1250,1739,1766]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.3" pageId="1" pageNumber="278" unit="m" value="1150.0" valueMax="2000.0" valueMin="300.0">300–2000 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
